But although phenomena are properly the appearances of things, but not ideas, or express the inner and absolute quality of objects, their cognition is nevertheless os the truest. For 111 1116 first place, being apprehended sensual concepts, they, being consequences, witness the presence of the object, contrary to Idealism3 and as regards judgments concerning that which is sensuously known, since truth in judging con- sists in the agreement of the predicate with the given subject, and since the concept of the subject as a phenomenon is given only by relation to the sensuous cognitive faculty, the sensuously observable predicates being given according to the same, it is plain that the representations of subject and predicate are made according to common laws, and hence give occasion for perfectly true cognition.
